<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,356,1103]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,898,923]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[345,571,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavum">
<emphasis box="[345,571,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Allometopon flavum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[704,847,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,847,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Allometopon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1001,1124,898,923]" name="Seychelles" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
, and still represented solely by the male 
<typeStatus box="[288,390,934,959]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">holotype</typeStatus>
. While the description and available photographs of the poorly preserved 
<typeStatus box="[1214,1262,936,960]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
cannot provide a through description of this species, it appears to be allied to the 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1000,970,995]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palpale">
<emphasis box="[884,1000,970,995]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. palpale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, specifically, with 
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1376,971,995]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acum">
<emphasis box="[1284,1376,971,995]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. acum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="69.[151,264,1774,1797]" captionTargetBox="[250,1336,195,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@69.[250,1336,195,1751]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Allometopon acum spec. nov.; 1: photo, dorsal; 2: photo, lateral; 3: external male genitalia, left lateral; 4: same, posterior; 5: internal male genitalia, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258767/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,163,1007,1031]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[231,328,1006,1031]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hybos">
<emphasis box="[231,248,1007,1030]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[263,328,1006,1031]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">hybos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[345,444,1006,1031]" captionStart="FIGURES 120 – 124" captionStartId="90.[151,264,1966,1989]" captionTargetBox="[182,1411,183,1942]" captionTargetId="figure@90.[182,1411,183,1943]" captionTargetPageId="90" captionText="FIGURES 120 – 124. Allometopon hybos Sasakawa, holotype; 120: photo, dorsal; 121: same, lateral; 122: external genitalia, posterior; 123: same, right lateral; 124: internal genitalia, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258788/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[399,444,1007,1031]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="120.0">120</number>
</figureCitation>
), which are yellow species with similarly pale setae and a black first flagellomere. It is nearly inseparable from 
<taxonomicName box="[438,539,1042,1067]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hybos">
<emphasis box="[438,539,1042,1067]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. hybos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(southeast Asia), and the examination of new material is required to better differentiate the two and describe the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
